$lang['The hexadecimal, or base-16, system was designed to emulate some of the same properties as the decimal system. In other words, it was created to make things easier for us humans. The number 423 has 16 digits instead of 10 digits available in a decimal system. This is because hexadecimal uses a base of 16 symbols instead of 10. After F, the order begins again with 0 and so on and so forth until we get to 15 which is notated as F.'] = 'Hexadecimal, walima base-16, sitɛmu dabɔra walasa ka decimal system ka jogo kelen dɔw ladege. O kɔrɔ ye ko a dabɔra walisa ka kow nɔgɔya anw hadamadenw ma. Jateden 423 bɛ ni jateden 16 ye sanni jateden 10 ka sɔrɔ jateden tannan na. O bɛ Kɛ k’a sababu Kɛ hexadecimal bɛ baara Kɛ ni basigi ye min ye taamaʃyɛn 16 ye 10 nɔ na. F kɔ fɛ, siginiden bɛ Daminɛ kokura ni 0 ye ani o cogo kelen na fo ka Se 15 ma min bɛ sɛbɛn ko F.';
$lang['Hexadecimal encoding reduces the number of digits by a factor of eight when compared to the decimal system. Additionally, hexadecimal numbers have an information density that is twice as high as decimal numbers do. So, why should you bother learning this funky little numbering scheme? Because it can make your life easier! When working with digital systems or data transmission, using hex will save you time and energy when decoding cryptic messages or data streams.'] = 'Hexadecimal kodɔnni bɛ dɔ bɔ jateden hakɛ la ni 8 ye n’i y’a suma ni tannan sigicogo ye. Ka fara o kan, jateden wɔɔrɔnanw ka kunnafoni hakɛ bɛ caya ni jateden tannanw ta ye siɲɛ fila. O la sa, mun na i ka kan k’i yɛrɛ sɛgɛn ka nin nimɔrɔ fitinin funky in dege? Sabu o bɛ se k’i ka ɲɛnamaya nɔgɔya! Ni aw bɛ baara kɛ ni nizɛri sitɛmuw ye walima ni kunnafonidilanw ye, ni aw bɛ baara kɛ ni hex ye, o bɛna aw ka waati ni fanga bɔ i la ni i bɛ cikan gundo walima kunnafonidilanw dekodɔn.';
